To fully answer your question, it is also interesting to ask "What is the real world usage of OpenAI's compuational power so far?" I will attempt to do so below:

OpenAI is a sophisticated outfit with deep pockets but nothing they are doing is necessarily novel. ChatGPT is a research project that has been aggressively marketed as ground-breaking and a sign that we are on the precipice of the machines taking over. Neither is true and it is important that people like yourself do research to educate the broader public about this truth - we appreciate your work. The reality is: human intelligence is incredibly nuanced and takes many forms (text, visual, sound, etc.) - the fact that LLMs are trained purely on text-based data today should allow one to reason that we are not on the precipice of uncontrollable intelligence (i.e., if human intelligence is dependent on text, visual and sound knowledge and LLMs are trained purely on text knowledge, we can say that machines do not yet have human intelligence)

So what is OpenAI doing and what has their computational power done so far? Well, it has awakened the broader public to the fact that AI can be both powerful and useful - this is bringing more talent into this industry and making the broader public aware of AI and its potential. Now, we must make sure the public is fully aware of where we stand and does not succomb to clips of "experts" declaring this technology to be so unsafe that only they can control it. In a literal, real-world sense, I am sure programmers have used ChatGPT to enhance the efficiency of their work, and others perhaps to assist in writing essays or e-mails. On the enterprise level, there seem to be several flashy headlines, but we have yet to see metrics for how OpenAI has helped companies create meaningful value. In other words, it is still very early and many are working to figure out exactly where value will accrue

As far as Bittensor is concerned, anything any corporation can do, the open-source community can do as well. No company has a monopoly on good ideas and as a result, open-source is only ever a few months behind the tech giants. As compute costs continue to rise, open-source looks even more attractive relative to big tech, and Bittensor, as a network that incentivizes compute and expertise from all over the world, becomes even better positioned to serve as the common infrastructure for AI development

Our network is still young and growing, but we very much believe it is day one not only for Bittensor but for this entire industry. As big tech apps become increasingly sophisticated, so will ours. And over time, we believe the power of the world will outshine the power of any one company, no matter how well-funded, credentialed or sexy they look from the outside

Thanks for taking an interest in what we are building, and please reach out if we can do anything to help with your piece

I know this.  But it's an important distinction.  The validator is the gateway to the network.  It is the thing you ask questions of.  And it earns TAO.  So if the third-party app developer has their own validator (i.e., thing to query), then they are earning TAO, and it may impact the decisions they make with regards to whether they charge their customers a fee and if so, how much.  

If they have their own validator, they will need TAO to stake to it in order to remain competitive.
If they *don't* have a validator of their own, they will have to use someone else's. Whether or not the validator charges for this service and if they do, *how* they do so, is up to the validator.

Likewise, if a third-party app developer has their own validator,  it's up to them to decide how they're going to deal with stake, and whether they'll charge their customers, and if they do charge, how and in what currency or token.

Maybe an app provider with a validator says, "hey, if you stake TAO to my validator, you'll get free or discounted service".  Or maybe they just say "pay me a subscription fee through PayPal in the currency of your choice, and I'll handle it on my end."  There are all kinds of ways to deal with it.

Eventually (timeline not announced, but I think a ways off) I think the plan is for validators to no longer earn any tao through validating. Instead, miners will earn 100% of emissions, and validators  might actually need to pay tao in order to validate (in essence, paying in order to operate a gateway to the network). At that point, a validator would earn a profit by charging developers who want to build apps for access to the network.
